In the process, Lewis also articulated a few unvarnished truths about the P=
ost=E2=80=99s business: =E2=80=9CYour audience has halved in recent years,=
=E2=80=9D he told his journalists. =E2=80=9CPeople are not reading your stu=
ff. I can=E2=80=99t sugarcoat it anymore.=E2=80=9D This memorable admonishm=
ent stressed the urgency of the Post=E2=80=99s challenges, but it also fore=
shadowed a new tone and tenor from the front office, and a new mandate for =
the notoriously disgruntled staff: Get with the program, or get out. Indeed=
, when the Post=E2=80=99s union protested Lewis=E2=80=99s recent return-to-=
office mandate, he told them he=E2=80=99d kindly accept the resignations of=
 any W.F.H. dead-enders. And as I noted last month, neither he nor Bezos we=
re terribly bothered by the departure of morally righteous journalists who =
protested the decision to forgo a presidential endorsement of Kamala
Harris. As with any business transformation, they probably welcomed the tur=
nover.

In a best-case scenario, Lewis would use the anointment of a new executive =
editor as an opportunity to further nudge the Post out of its era of inerti=
a. This new leader would not merely be tasked with overseeing a newsroom, b=
ut also establishing a new mandate for the coverage, and, indeed, even a ne=
w identity for the paper itself=E2=80=94one divorced not just from the rudd=
erlessness of the Buzbee era, but also from the =E2=80=9CDemocracy Dies in =
Darkness=E2=80=9D posturing of the Baron era, and perhaps with a little les=
s nostalgia for Bradlee and Graham and Woodward and Bernstein.

Presumably, this new mandate would align with Bezos=E2=80=99s own desire to=
 restore the Post to its former place as the paper of record for official W=
ashington and, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before, as an at least semi-nonpartisa=
n organization servicing all
Americans, rather than a regional edition of the Times political report ser=
vicing anxious liberals. At best, the Post might once again establish itsel=
f as a compelling and authoritative source on the culture of power and infl=
uence in Washington, with its finger on the pulse of not just the White Hou=
se and Capitol Hill but also Cleveland Park and Kalorama. For now, Lewis wo=
uld at least like someone who can inspire staff to come into the newsroom a=
nd file a little more often.

The challenge, of course, is finding that leader among a particularly limit=
ed talent pool of editors who are actually willing to inherit all the afore=
mentioned challenges, and whose identity won=E2=80=99t establish a second t=
heater of war. Earlier this fall, executive recruitment firm Spencer Stuart=
 approached dozens of candidates on the Post=E2=80=99s behalf, including Ti=
mes managing editor Carolyn Ryan, Cliff Levy, and other members of the Time=
s
masthead=E2=80=94the majority of whom did not engage in anything beyond pre=
liminary talks. Levy, who now oversees the Times=E2=80=99s Athletic and Wir=
ecutter, did engage beyond preliminary talks, and is among the handful of c=
andidates who interviewed with Lewis and submitted memos outlining their ne=
ar- and long-term visions for the newsroom. There are other external candid=
ates as well, though I don=E2=80=99t yet have their names.

Meanwhile, as previously noted, there are two internal candidates vying for=
 the position: Murray, the acting executive editor, and managing editor Mat=
ea Gold, herself a 12-year veteran of the paper. Both have their strengths =
and weaknesses=E2=80=94don=E2=80=99t we all=E2=80=94but, crucially, neither=
 is seen as the kind of change agent that Lewis would presumably favor to l=
ead the newsroom. Frankly, they=E2=80=99re just hometown Cliff Levy types=
=E2=80=94well-pedigreed and smart, yes and of course, but institutionalists=
 without track records of innovation and
risk-taking. Long before his current sinecure essentially serving as the Wi=
recutter and Athletic=E2=80=99s liaisons to the mothership, Levy ran the il=
l-fated NYT Now app project, where he liked to point out the novel quirk of=
 a Times product saying =E2=80=9Chello=E2=80=9D to its readers. Like others=
, he=E2=80=99s a multi-Pulitzer winner who commands respect and has been pr=
omoted out of power.

Murray, who served as the Journal=E2=80=99s editor-in-chief when Lewis was =
its publisher, may be his preferred candidate of the two, but many in the n=
ewsroom are unsurprisingly said to favor their longtime colleague. And, ala=
s, he may have to settle on one or the other. But, boy, would that seem lik=
e a waste of time and energy=E2=80=94and, frankly, a nonsensical conclusion=
 to Lewis=E2=80=99s year of magical thinking. He arrived, after all, to ban=
dage up a bleeding business, offer a compelling (if not entirely lucid) vis=
ion of its future, and signal significant forthcoming change. To do all tha=
t=E2=80=A6 and
then somehow suggest that the leading candidate was in the building all alo=
ng=E2=80=A6 would seem like a bizarre management decision. Why come up with=
