=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F4%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F3%2F24%29&utm_medium=3D=
email_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

What are you hearing from your friends in the bureau since we=E2=80=99ve le=
arned that Kash Patel is the nominee, and what do you think the reaction is=
 among the rank and file, both in the Hoover building and across the countr=
y?

Figliuzzi: I talked to a number of executives at the headquarters who polis=
hed up their r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9s as soon as Trump was named as winner of the =
election, and are out there actively pursuing other careers. The chief conc=
ern is the degree to which Patel, in that position, is going to impact the =
field offices. If we start having politicians look at case openings and clo=
sings, if we start getting to the point where corruption cases aren=E2=80=
=99t opened on Republican elected officials, if counterintelligence cases a=
re not allowed to be opened, we=E2=80=99re going to have a problem.

To the extent that the F.B.I.
will still be made up largely of lifers and not political appointees, how w=
ill the culture clash play out when the appointees who don=E2=80=99t give a=
 shit about their norms and customs are intertwined with the F.B.I. agents =
who honor and respect them?

Figliuzzi: The F.B.I. employees=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s 37,000 of them=E2=80=
=94take their posts extremely seriously. There=E2=80=99s an entire structur=
e to keep us all on the same sheet of music with regard to our collective c=
ore values, the kind of core values that we=E2=80=99re seeing no sign of in=
 Kash Patel. So that clash is going to occur rather immediately. I=E2=80=99=
m sure the Agents Association and other law firms are ready to go on challe=
nging him. Even if he=E2=80=99s not ultimately confirmed, Patel can do a tr=
emendous amount of damage in seven months as an acting F.B.I. lead.

Bannon, Bondi & Hunter

What do you think of Pam Bondi as the next attorney general of the United S=
tates?

Weissmann: I=E2=80=99ve described this as being cautiously pessimistic. On =
the plus side, compared to other proposed nominations, she=E2=80=99s somebo=
dy who=E2=80=99s had a long career in law enforcement. So it=E2=80=99s not =
like she=E2=80=99s bringing nothing to the table in terms of understanding =
the craft and what it means to lead an office. On the other hand, what I=E2=
=80=99m missing from her statements [about investigating the investigators =
of Russiagate, for instance] is any factual predication, and the F.B.I. is =
trained to understand that you don=E2=80=99t take actions without factual p=
redication to justify the activity; the goal is to keep building those fact=
s.

Another thing I think is a little bit of a plus: She=E2=80=99s not totally =
shameless. She=E2=80=99s enough of a career
prosecutor to understand that it=E2=80=99s wrong to just investigate everyb=
ody. What remains to be seen is how she conducts herself and what she says =
about that in her confirmation hearing=E2=80=94and then, if she=E2=80=99s c=
onfirmed, how much she is going to take that to heart in her role as attorn=
ey general.

When you hear Steve Bannon say the president is also the chief magistrate, =
is that true?

Weissmann: It=E2=80=99s true in the sense that there=E2=80=99s nothing in t=
he Constitution that the Supreme Court has found that requires a president =
to hold off from telling his attorney general to prosecute certain people a=
nd not prosecute others, absent there being selective prosecution claims. T=
hat=E2=80=99s something the president can do. The precedent in the recent T=
rump immunity decision is all about presidential power and the president=E2=
=80=99s preclusive and conclusive power to deal with his Department of Just=
ice.

What=E2=80=99s your take on Biden=E2=80=99s decision to pardon his
son Hunter, despite having assured the country a lot of times that he would=
n=E2=80=99t do this?

Weissmann: When looking at the gun charge, as a prosecutor for over 20 year=
s and a defense lawyer for about 10 years, I don=E2=80=99t know of any case=
 that would be prosecuted like Hunter=E2=80=99s was. It seems to me that th=
e only reason Hunter was in that position is because he=E2=80=99s the son o=
f Joe. If he was Hunter Smith instead of Hunter Biden, I don't think he wou=
ld have been under investigation or ever prosecuted and treated this way. W=
e=E2=80=99re not just talking about issues of holding Hunter responsible fo=
r the crimes he=E2=80=99s been convicted of, but we=E2=80=99re talking abou=
t a vendetta. So, to me, that would apply to Hunter Biden and others that J=
oe Biden has the power to alleviate that kind of retaliatory action by an i=
ncoming administration.

Figliuzzi: I think two things can be true at the same time. We could view t=
his as a horribly unfortunate set of events and
wish it hadn=E2=80=99t happened, and at the same time, we can say we unders=
tand why it happened. I spent 25 years enforcing federal law, and it pains =
me whenever the justice system is further eroded. It=E2=80=99s eroded enoug=
h=E2=80=94largely because of Donald Trump, not Joe Biden=E2=80=94but this d=
oesn=E2=80=99t help with public credibility. At the same time, I=E2=80=99m =
also the father of adult sons. The concept that Pam Bondi is going to overs=
ee the Bureau of Prisons under a Trump administration, where my son could b=
e subjected to everything under the sun if he=E2=80=99s incarcerated, might=
 be enough for me to say, I=E2=80=99m not letting that happen.

