             <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In the process, =
Lewis also articulated a few unvarnished truths about the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=
=99s business: =E2=80=9CYour audience has halved in recent years,=E2=80=9D =
he told his journalists. =E2=80=9CPeople are not reading your stuff. I can=
=E2=80=99t sugarcoat it anymore.=E2=80=9D This memorable admonishment stres=
sed the urgency of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s challenges, but it also foresh=
adowed a new tone and tenor from the front office, and a new mandate for th=
e notoriously disgruntled staff: Get with the program, or get out. Indeed, =
when the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s union protested Lewis=E2=80=99s recent retur=
n-to-office mandate, he told them he=E2=80=99d kindly accept the resignatio=
ns of any W.F.H. dead-enders. And as I noted last month, neither he nor Bez=
os were terribly bothered by the departure of morally righteous journalists=
 who protested the decision to forgo a presidential endorsement of <b>Kamal=
a
Harris</b>. As with any business transformation, they probably welcomed the=
 turnover.<br/><br/>In a best-case scenario, Lewis would use the anointment=
 of a new executive editor as an opportunity to further nudge the <i>Post <=
/i>out of its era of inertia. This new leader would not merely be tasked wi=
th overseeing a newsroom, but also establishing a new mandate for the cover=
age, and, indeed, even a new <i>identity</i> for the paper itself=E2=80=94o=
ne divorced not just from the rudderlessness of the Buzbee era, but also fr=
om the =E2=80=9CDemocracy Dies in Darkness=E2=80=9D posturing of the <b>Bar=
on</b> era, and perhaps with a little less nostalgia for <b>Bradlee</b> and=
 <b>Graham</b> and <b>Woodward</b> and <b>Bernstein</b>. <br/><br/>Presumab=
ly, this new mandate would align with Bezos=E2=80=99s own desire to restore=
 the <i>Post</i> to its former place as the paper of record for official Wa=
shington and, as I=E2=80=99ve noted before, as an at least <i>semi</i>-nonp=
artisan organization servicing <i>all
</i>Americans, rather than a regional edition of the <i>Times</i> political=
 report servicing anxious liberals. At best, the <i>Post </i>might once aga=
in establish itself as a compelling and authoritative source on the <i>cult=
ure </i>of power and influence in Washington, with its finger on the pulse =
of not just the White House and Capitol Hill but also Cleveland Park and Ka=
lorama. For now, Lewis would at least like someone who can inspire staff to=
 come into the newsroom and file a little more often.<br/><br/>The challeng=
e, of course, is finding that leader among a particularly limited talent po=
ol of editors who are actually willing to inherit all the aforementioned ch=
allenges, and whose identity won=E2=80=99t establish a second theater of wa=
r. Earlier this fall, executive recruitment firm Spencer Stuart approached =
dozens of candidates on the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s behalf, including <i>Time=
s </i>managing editor <b>Carolyn Ryan</b>, <b>Cliff Levy</b>, and other mem=
bers of the <i>Times</i>
masthead=E2=80=94the majority of whom did not engage in anything beyond pre=
liminary talks. Levy, who now oversees the <i>Times</i>=E2=80=99s Athletic =
and Wirecutter, <i>did</i> engage beyond preliminary talks, and is among th=
e handful of candidates who interviewed with Lewis and submitted memos outl=
ining their near- and long-term visions for the newsroom. There are other e=
xternal candidates as well, though I don=E2=80=99t yet have their names.<br=
/><br/>Meanwhile, as previously noted, there are two internal candidates vy=
ing for the position: Murray, the acting executive editor, and managing edi=
tor <b>Matea Gold</b>, herself a 12-year veteran of the paper. Both have th=
eir strengths and weaknesses=E2=80=94don=E2=80=99t we all=E2=80=94but, cruc=
ially, neither is seen as the kind of change agent that Lewis would presuma=
bly favor to lead the newsroom. Frankly, they=E2=80=99re just hometown Clif=
f Levy types=E2=80=94well-pedigreed and smart, <i>yes and of course</i>, bu=
t institutionalists without track records of innovation and
risk-taking. Long before his current sinecure essentially serving as the Wi=
recutter and Athletic=E2=80=99s liaisons to the mothership, Levy ran the il=
l-fated NYT Now app project, where he liked to point out the novel quirk of=
 a <i>Times </i>product saying =E2=80=9Chello=E2=80=9D to its readers. Like=
 others, he=E2=80=99s a multi-Pulitzer winner who commands respect and has =
been promoted out of power.<br/><br/>Murray, who served as the <i>Journal</=
i>=E2=80=99s editor-in-chief when Lewis was its publisher, may be his prefe=
rred candidate of the two, but many in the newsroom are unsurprisingly said=
 to favor their longtime colleague. And, alas, he may have to settle on one=
 or the other. But, boy, would that seem like a waste of time and energy=E2=
=80=94and, frankly, a nonsensical conclusion to Lewis=E2=80=99s year of mag=
ical thinking. He arrived, after all, to bandage up a bleeding business, of=
fer a compelling (if not entirely lucid) vision of its future, and signal s=
ignificant forthcoming change. To do all that=E2=80=A6 and
then somehow suggest that the leading candidate was in the building all alo=
ng=E2=80=A6 would seem like a bizarre management decision. Why come up with=
 a plan if you aren=E2=80=99t going to bring in someone to execute it? Seem=
s like Lewis would have a hard time explaining that one to his boss. =E2=80=
=94<i>Dylan Byers</i><br/><br/><i>And, finally, Heilemann on the Kash sitch=
=E2=80=A6</i><br/></td>
            </tr>
